        the galaxies have elongated projected axis ratios at 4.4$\mu$m,
        suggesting that the population is disk-dominated or prolate.
        Most of the galaxies appear red at all radii, suggesting
        significant dust attenuation throughout. We refer to these red,
        disky, HST-dark galaxies as Ultra-red Flattened Objects (UFOs).
        With $r_e$(F444W)$\sim1-2$\raisebox{-0.5ex}\textasciitildekpc,
        the galaxies are similar in size to compact massive galaxies at
        $z\sim2$ and the cores of massive galaxies and S0s at $z\sim0$.
        The stellar masses, sizes, and morphologies of the sample
        suggest that some could be progenitors of lenticular or fast-
        rotating galaxies in the local Universe. The existence of this
        population suggests that our previous censuses of the universe
        may have missed massive, dusty edge-on disks, in addition to
        dust-obscured starbursts.}",
